In the [[Outline of physical science|physical sciences]] and [[natural science]] a '''predoctoral fellow''' ('''pre-doc''') refers to a researcher who has a [[bachelor's degree]], but not a [[doctorate]].  As the name implies, predoctoral fellows often use their time as a fellow to develop their skills and résumé before applying to [[graduate school]]. They differ from lab managers or technicians in that they primarily pursue research, rather than maintain the day-to-day function of a lab, and may have external funding to support their research or educational activities, but typically are also reliant on the support of a research mentor whose lab they work in.{{Citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence}}

In [[Mathematics]] and some Science disciplines, typically a pre-doc is somebody already registered in a Ph.D. program at a host university to work together with a professor in a different topic with respect to his/her topic.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2017}}

